  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Often, the data points to label are chosen greedily by identifying the training instance whose labeling would most positively influence the model (in expectation).",
    "Quantifying each unlabeled instance's true influence at each active learning iteration may be prohibitive, so influence estimation techniques are often used to quantify each remaining unlabeled instance's marginal contribution at a given iteration (Liu et al., 2021).",
    "With this broad perspective on influence analysis and related concepts in mind, we transition to focusing on specific influence analysis methods in the next two sections.",
    "Training instances can only influence a model if they are used during training.",
    "As Sect. 3.1.2 describes in the context of linear regression, one method to measure influence just trains a model with and without some instance; influence is then defined as the difference in these two models' behavior."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
